docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Senate voted on Monday to temporarily reinstate a handful of newly expired F.B.I. tools for investigating terrorism and espionage in an attempt to grant lawmakers time to sort out broader differences over surveillance laws and move to addressing the coronavirus pandemic.

headline.main: Senate, Bidding for Time, Tries to Temporarily Revive Spy Tools
headline.print_headline: Senate Votes to Temporarily Revive F.B.I. Spy Tools

docs.abstract: As long as Congress has met, votes have been cast only in person. A growing group of lawmakers are pushing to change that in the age of coronavirus.
docs.snippet: As long as Congress has met, votes have been cast only in person. A growing group of lawmakers are pushing to change that in the age of coronavirus.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Under pressure to upend centuries of tradition to respond to a growing pandemic, congressional leaders reluctantly agreed on Thursday to at least study the feasibility of allowing lawmakers to vote from home, after two House members tested positive for the coronavirus and a dozen others were quarantined.

headline.main: Coronavirus Is in the Capitol. Some Lawmakers Think They Shouldn’t Be.
headline.print_headline: Lawmakers Resurrect Question of Congress Voting From Home

docs.abstract: The operational effect may be limited because the surveillance laws remain in effect for existing investigations.
docs.snippet: The operational effect may be limited because the surveillance laws remain in effect for existing investigations.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — House Democrats left the capital on Friday after passing the $2 trillion coronavirus relief legislation without taking up a Senate bill to temporarily revive three expired F.B.I. surveillance tools for terrorism and espionage investigations, ensuring that the laws will remain lapsed at least until the Senate returns from vacation next month.

headline.main: House Departs Without Vote to Extend Expired F.B.I. Spy Tools
headline.print_headline: House Democrats Wrap Up Without Reviving Spy Tools

docs.abstract: The White House’s coronavirus response coordinator drew criticism for comments she made about ventilator shortages, and for gushing praise of President Trump.
docs.snippet: The White House’s coronavirus response coordinator drew criticism for comments she made about ventilator shortages, and for gushing praise of President Trump.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The White House coronavirus task force has featured two trusted medical voices, diplomatic but authoritative, able to gently push back on President Trump without incurring his wrath: Drs. Anthony S. Fauci, the director of the National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases, and Deborah L. Birx, the coronavirus response coordinator.

headline.main: For Dr. Deborah Birx, Urging Calm Has Come With Heavy Criticism
headline.print_headline: For Trump Adviser, Urging Calm Has Come With Heavy Criticism

docs.abstract: In a signing statement, the president undermined a key safeguard Democrats had insisted upon as a condition of approving $500 billion in corporate relief in the $2 trillion law.
docs.snippet: In a signing statement, the president undermined a key safeguard Democrats had insisted upon as a condition of approving $500 billion in corporate relief in the $2 trillion law.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — When President Trump signed the $2 trillion economic stabilization package on Friday to respond to the coronavirus pandemic, he undercut a crucial safeguard that Democrats insisted upon as a condition of agreeing to include a $500 billion corporate bailout fund.

headline.main: Trump Suggests He Can Gag Inspector General for Stimulus Bailout Program

docs.abstract: The president, who has watched the economy plunge amid social distancing measures, says restrictions will be reassessed.
docs.snippet: The president, who has watched the economy plunge amid social distancing measures, says restrictions will be reassessed.
docs.lead_paragraph: President Trump on Sunday night said that the government would reassess the recommended period for keeping businesses shut and millions of workers at home after this week, amid millions of job losses caused by the efforts to contain the spread of the novel coronavirus.

headline.main: Trump Says Coronavirus Cure Cannot ‘Be Worse Than the Problem Itself’

docs.abstract: Thousands of American and NATO troops are scheduled to leave in the next few months, but quarantine procedures are complicating those efforts.
docs.snippet: Thousands of American and NATO troops are scheduled to leave in the next few months, but quarantine procedures are complicating those efforts.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The U.S. commander in Afghanistan is halting American and allied troops from entering Afghanistan and, in turn, preventing some troops from leaving, for the next month, American and European officials said. The planning reflects mounting concerns as the coronavirus has spread in the country in recent days.

headline.main: Coronavirus Disrupts Troop Withdrawal in Afghanistan

docs.snippet: The late-night announcement was the latest step by the central bank to keep financial markets functioning during the coronavirus crisis.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Federal Reserve said late Wednesday night that it would offer emergency loans to money market mutual funds, its latest in a series of steps to keep the financial system functioning and prop up the economy as it spirals toward recession during the coronavirus pandemic.

headline.main: Federal Reserve Gives Emergency Aid to Mutual Funds

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump on Wednesday defended his increasingly frequent practice of calling the coronavirus the “Chinese Virus,” ignoring a growing chorus of criticism that it is racist and anti-Chinese.

docs.abstract: Sharp debates among top administration aides reveal divisions in how to confront Iran and its Shiite militia proxies in Iraq.
docs.snippet: Sharp debates among top administration aides reveal divisions in how to confront Iran and its Shiite militia proxies in Iraq.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump was getting ready to declare the coronavirus a “national emergency,” but inside the White House last Thursday, a tense debate erupted among the president and his top advisers on a far different subject: whether the United States should escalate military action against Iran, a longtime American rival that has been devastated by the epidemic.

headline.main: As Iran Reels, Trump Aides Clash Over Escalating Military Showdown
headline.print_headline: As Iran Reels, Trump Aides Clash Over Escalating Military Action
